<span class="name"><a name="99394"></a></span><span class="postdetails">#1:&nbsp;<font color=black><b>Targeting and Mez</b> Author:&nbsp;<b>cdoe</b>,&nbsp;</font></span><span class="postdetails"><font color=black></font></span>
<a href="viewtopic.php?p=99394#99394"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails"><font color=black>Posted: Thu Mar 17, 2005 2:02 pm</font><span class="gen"><br>
</td></tr>
<tr><td class="printline">
<span class="postbody">I was involved in a Nek Castle raid with my guild last night. I’m a level 32 illusionist. I was one of the lower members of the group, so we were cutting through it like butter. We had a serious issue near the end and wiped to a good number of beetles including a named. There were many causes for this including overconfidence on everyone’s part, lack of assisting (splitting the mobs), bad luck etc. It was a less than optimal group makeup but I want to keep the focus off that.
<br />

<br />
The individual mobs were not particularly difficult. I was generally keeping about four locked down at a time, while my group were splitting the rest, between two and four more, always a mix of more than one encounter group. 
<br />

<br />
There is a tendency for a tank type who is not used to playing with an enchanter to try and use whatever means are necessary to pull a mob off a healer, which means breaking mez. I generally don’t complain about this much, because it comes down to their faith in themselves vs. me being able to get it off the healer first. It only becomes a problem when the fight has already gone south. 
<br />

<br />
Then there’s my own problem with hotkey-targeting. I’m not sure I know exactly what I’m doing here but I have my target-next-encounter-member key handy, then use the mouse to switch between encounters. I tend to get confused fairly easily when trying to lock down five or more mobs, so at that point I switch to mouse targeting everything, which brings its own problems.
<br />

<br />
I tend to put myself in the center the a circle of mobs, toggling on and off mouse look to circle and mouse-target each mob. I know this seems counterproductive with all the extra work but it means all my targets are very large and visible, so psychologically I’m always drawn here when in a sticky situation.  I’m pretty sure even keyboard targeting won’t switch to a mob that’s around a corner, so position is critical, especially indoors.
<br />

<br />
Finally the UI tends to cause problems after very so often. One culprit is that HO wheel. I never have a good place to put it and it always comes up when I least expect it, right in my way. I’m sure I can download a smaller one from eq2nterface, regardless, there is never enough screen.
<br />

<br />
I never use AOE mez, incidentally, I don’t even understand how I might use it effectively. I just got an AOE stun, but there is no maintained effects icon, so I’m never sure when it is going to wear off.
<br />

<br />
I’ve saved the day before, and I think I’m relatively good at playing an enchanter, but I want to get better. I want to save the day the next time this happens and I want to be able to lock down more mobs without mistakes when I need to. Can anyone else share your ideas about technique and strategy along with keyboard and UI layout? Anything that might give me some ideas to play around with would be great. Thanks!</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
</td></tr>
<br />
